{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502834"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:50:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:50:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1900"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1900"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.38,0.09,0.16,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1900"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52592"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1900"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1900"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37954"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"107"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7271"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7461"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15318"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42423"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52592"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of pain and redness under her left breast. She feels generally unwell and complains of subjective fevers. She has never experienced similar symptoms before and has no history of breast problems. Her medical history includes type 2 diabetes and irritable bowel syndrome. She takes metformin as her only regular medication. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 124/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.7\u00b0C. Her BMI is 28 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. There is a tender, warm, erythematous patch with poorly demarcated margins in the left inframammary fold extending to the surrounding skin (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tinea","Cellulitis","Flexural psoriasis","Candidiasis","Erythrasma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ecellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E. Cellulitis is an acute bacterial infection causing inflammation of the deep dermis and surrounding subcutaneous tissue. It is most frequently caused by \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E (group A streptococcus) or \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E. The poorly demarcated erythema, warmth, tenderness, and systemic symptoms (fever, feeling unwell) are typical features of cellulitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETinea\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as ringworm, is a fungal infection that typically presents as a pruritic, annular plaque with central clearing and a peripheral scaly red rim. This patient\u0027s presentation lacks the characteristic annular appearance and scaling of tinea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexural psoriasis\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune chronic inflammatory disorder that presents as a non-tender erythematous plaque with well-defined borders, sometimes scaly. It is usually mildly pruritic and does not typically cause fever or systemic symptoms. The acute onset and systemic symptoms in this case make psoriasis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECandidiasis\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by the yeast \u003Cem\u003ECandida albicans\u003C/em\u003E. It commonly involves skin flexures and causes pruritus, but typically does not present with fever or systemic symptoms. Candida intertrigo is usually symmetrical, and \u0027satellite\u0027 pustules or papules outside the rim of the rash are characteristic. The lack of pruritus and satellite lesions makes candidiasis less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythrasma\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic superficial infection of the skin flexures caused by \u003Cem\u003ECorynebacterium minutissimum\u003C/em\u003E. It presents as dark discoloration of the body folds and is most commonly asymptomatic, although it can be pruritic. The acute onset, systemic symptoms, and lack of characteristic discoloration make erythrasma an unlikely diagnosis for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s history of diabetes is significant, as it is a risk factor for developing cellulitis. Diabetes can impair immune function and increase susceptibility to bacterial infections. The location of the infection in the inframammary fold is also consistent with cellulitis, as this area can be prone to moisture and friction, creating an environment conducive to bacterial growth.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cellulitis is an acute bacterial infection of the deep dermis and subcutaneous tissue most commonly caused by Streptococcus pyogenes.","Cellulitis typically presents with poorly demarcated erythema, warmth, tenderness, and systemic symptoms such as fever.","Diabetes is a risk factor for developing cellulitis."],"references":["Gunderson CG, Martinello RA. A systematic review of bacteremias in cellulitis and erysipelas. J Infect. 2012 Feb;64(2):148-55. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22101078/","Raff AB, Kroshinsky D. Cellulitis: A Review. JAMA. 2016 Jul 19;316(3):325-37. Available at: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/article-abstract/2533510"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37954"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1900"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17954"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17954"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9cc3f7ff-dfad-40af-a1fa-8fcc32702653.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9cc3f7ff-dfad-40af-a1fa-8fcc32702653.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37954"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-07T12:01:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-07T12:02:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1900"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52592"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"